Line 329 of bamboo-agent.sh reads:

{noformat}
su -m $RUN_AS_USER -c "\"$REALPATH\" $2"
{noformat}

$PATH is then hardcoded down the script to include only $JAVA_HOME/bin and what's in /etc/login.defs.

This has the effect of generally munging otherwise valid environment configurations for specific paths to specific tools the build agent may need; 

I've ended up changing the above line to:

{noformat}
su - $RUN_AS_USER -c "\"$REALPATH\" $2"
{noformat}

so as to be able to handle PATH outside what the startup scripts are attempting to do, but it would be nice to either a) document that more effectively or b) provide an override mechanism so I don't have to sed my way through the startup scripts every time we deploy a new agent.

A superset of BAM-2554 and BAM-3065, and a bit complicated, so I'll try and explain, but please ask for clarification if this doesn't make sense;

We have a number of loosely connected services building, testing and deploying via Bamboo. Any individual plan may successfully run and pass all its tests, but  when integrated with the rest of the system, cause unexpected behavior.

We _also_ have a comprehensive set of integration tests, designed to run against the overall system, ensuring a basic level of interoperability on a newly deployed service.

If the integration tests fail, we roll back the deployed service (Service A) to its previous version on our CI deployment servers until we can verify what the issues may be, so that the next service (Service B) that deploys won't a) mask an issue from the previous service or b) get effed due to an issue in a different service.

However, rolling back the deployment servers doesn't give us any indication in Bamboo that despite the unit tests succeeding for Service A, its a questionable build; BAM-2554 would allow us to manually mark that build as "failed"; BAM-3065 would give us a state between Success and Failure that would indicate questionability.

But, what I really want is a mechanism to mark a plan, stage or job as conditionally Successful based on the result of an interstitially inserted plan; in essence, aspect-oriented plans ...

In this situation, we'd add a marker or dependency on the overall success of plan for Service A as dependent on the Success of Plan B (integration testing) - if Plan B succeeds, mark Plan A as successful; if not, mark it as failed or questionable.

Moreover, I don't think that implementation in this way would increase the risk of circular dependency loops; while its possible to specify aspects that would end up depending back on the plan declaring the aspect, its no worse than the current ability to create cyclic dependency graphs using already existing functionality; moreover, since the state of the plan declaring the aspect would still be "Running", a fast failure would be easy to throw out: 

{noformat}
if (context.inAspect) { follow dependency tree; if (plan.dependency == self) { fail } }
{noformat}

Hopefully this makes sense, and I think it would dramatically increase the power available to complex situations in Bamboo.

